 Wight, Norwood in Middlesex and Surrey, or Northwood Farm in Okehampton and Northwood Farm in Morchard Bishop, both in Devon. The placenames mean ‘north or northern wood’, from Old English <i>north</i> ‘north, northern’ + <i>wudu</i> ‘wood’ or Middle English <i>north</i> + <i>wode</i>. Compare   Norrod  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Nard","meanings":["Altered form of English   Norwood  . Compare   Norrod  .","In some cases probably also French: from a short form of the personal name   Bernard  . Compare   Denard  ."]},{"name":"Norrod","meanings":["Altered form of English   Norwood  . It was further respelled to   Nard  ,   Norred  ,   Norrid  , and   Nored  .","History: Benjamin Isaac Norrod (1735–1816) came from Buckinghamshire, England, to MD in 1735, and moved on to Stewart County, TN."]}]},{"name":"Dorothy","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Usual English form of   Dorothea .  The name was not used in the Middle Ages, but was taken up in the 15th century and became common thereafter. It was borne by the American film star  Dorothy Lamour  (  1914–1996 , born  Dorothy Kaumeyer )."],"variants":[{"name":"Dorothee","meanings":["Usual English form of   Dorothea .  The name was not used in the Middle Ages, but was taken up in the 15th century and became common thereafter. It was borne by the American film star  Dorothy Lamour  (  1914–1996 , born  Dorothy Kaumeyer )."]},{"name":"Dorothie","meanings":["Usual English form of   Dorothea .  The name was not used in the Middle Ages, but was taken up in the 15th century and became common thereafter. It was borne by the American film star  Dorothy Lamour  (  1914–1996 , born  Dorothy Kaumeyer )."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Dorothy Norwood was born in 1418, in Coventry, Warwickshire, England, United Kingdom, her father, James Norwood, was 28 and her mother, Joan, was 24. She married Sir Thomas Hoo \"The Younger\" about 1439. They were the parents